HUNDREDS of youth and members of the police gathered at St George Hotel as the Department of Civilian Secretariat for Police Service is holding a first of its kind national youth crime prevention consultative summit. The summit was encouraged by President Cyril Ramaphosaâ€™s pronouncement of youth involvement in crime prevention strategies and is expected to attracted at least 500 people to the Irene hotel every morning until Thursday. Numerous pupils in school uniform were given seats in the front row alongside dignitaries. Deputy minister of police, Bongani Mkongi, welcomed the youth and the pupils and reminded them of the important role they could play In eliminating crime. Addressing the media, Mkongi said the youth of South Africa should not be inspired by coward criminals who hid behind masks and criticised the police and police minister Bheli Cele. To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window.  The summit will highlight ministerial objective plans that seek to remind the audience that, among other objectives: victims should be treated with respect and dignity and that victims should be assisted in a private room. One of the aims of the summit is to encourage the promotion and protection of the rights of woman, children and vulnerable groups. The event attracted youth from across all nine provinces. They sang, danced and also joined national police commissioner, Kehla Sitole, in singing the national anthem. The police are hoping to engage more and more young people during the summit and have an outcome that would have involved young people in the creation of a developmental crime prevention strategy.